can you trust everyone who says they are an independent financial adviser i'm looking for a mortgage ifa's are paid commission on the products they sell it is very possible that they will recommend a product to you that pays them the best commission and is not always the best product for you advisers at bank building societies tend to be paid a monthly salary and they are awarded bonuses for hitting sales targets so they will get paid regardless unfortunately most salaried advisers can only discuss products offered by the company that employs them they may not have the product on offer that is best for you as another ya member has already said if you want truly independent advise you need an adviser that is being paid solely by you there is a lot of information about product s and interest rates available on the internet so it may be worth you doing a bit of research yourself before you commit yourself in any way good luck Life insurance Investment bank Microeconomics Primerica Financial Services Mutual fund Tax Economy of Russia Principal-agent problem Debt Social Security (United States) Islamic banking Inflation Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Bank Insurance Cooperative Student loan Taxation in the United States National Kidney Foundation Singapore Gross domestic product Management Donald Trump FairTax Toronto-Dominion Bank Annuity Education in the People's Republic of China Bond Monetary policy Citigroup Internet fraud Electronic commerce Lehman Brothers Investment advisor Great Depression Capital accumulation Salary cap Advertising East Germany Anarchism and capitalism Housing cooperative Capitalism Financial markets Economy of India LiveJournal Progressive tax Schabir Shaik Trial Hedge fund Flat tax Personal finance Intellectual property Tesco Wal-Mart Federal National Mortgage Association Financial analyst Credit card Universal Studios Graduate school Security (finance) Bank fraud Amway U.S. public debt 401(k) Su